    {
      "id": "dd1c58e6553bad8cd81933c0dd25e6bc54e6f7ba",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-24 18:19:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nBuild Started http://newbuild.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/637/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "1ac313a243e764fc2a575afcee8c5f49ef62bf06",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-24 18:30:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI think the current structure of this patch risks ignoring errors that were not seen by the application:\n\nwrite1 - return error, set lli_write_rc, application rewrites\n         data for file\nwrite2 - return 0 (async RPC error not seen by application)\nfsync  - does not return error because lli_write_rc is set\n\nIt would be better to have ll_file_write_aio() check and clear the lli_async_rc() when it returns an error to the application.\n\nEven better than this (probably only for 2.x) is to get rid of lli_async_rc and loi_ar.ar_rc and use the normal kernel \"page error\" and \"address space error\" mechanisms to track errors.  That allows the errors to be cleared on a per-page basis if the pages are rewritten, and sync_page_range() will also return errors only for pages within that range instead of an error on another random page in the same file.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "675ae6bebe2d3e35ea14ed27a0b047bb54c93f08",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-24 18:38:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://newbuild.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/637/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a6adacb80d15f90d1542ac93b649d41148cc92c8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-25 01:51:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>write1 - return error, set lli_write_rc, application rewrites\n         data for file\n>write2 - return 0 (async RPC error not seen by application)\n>fsync  - does not return error because lli_write_rc is set\n\nAt the point of \"write2\" return 0, \"lli_write_rc\" is cleared also. So the logic of subsequent \"fsync\" is not affected by \"lli_write_rc\". On the other hand, I prefer to make \"lli_write_rc\" is per \"file structure\" based, not \"inode structure\" based.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "bede81294d834d0cb329f361462a0da042661a1d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-25 14:02:46.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "aff33ee048a0ea400713262efbdc7464e9f293f3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-25 14:02:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nBuild Started http://newbuild.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/646/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "359f564c90b3449cb622d4ffb8b0272e9f501e1c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-25 14:03:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI rename per-inode structure based 'lli_write_rc' as per file-structure based 'fd_last_write' to track the last write/fsync result (success or failure) through the 'file' structure. So when 'sys_close()' is called against the 'file' structure, we know whether the caller has known write/fsync failure or not, and then avoid report confused failure.\n\nAs for 'lli_async_rc', they do not conflict:\n1) if 'fd_last_write' is set, then means last write/fsync failed, and the caller has known that, so 'sys_close()->ll_flush()' returns success.\n2) if 'fd_last_write' is reset, then process as original logic\n\nIs anything wrong?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "27572c25c11cdd78ccf2ae7bd48a1c442c2c4704",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-05-25 14:21:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://newbuild.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/646/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
